\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 1) Scripts\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
There were numerous versions of the single-player story for "Freelancer."  The\par
one that ships in the game was begun around March of 2001 and was tweaked until\par
the end of 2002.  Included here are the first and final drafts.\par
\tab I've called it the "shooting script" because it underwent a minor amount\par
of tweaking as we created the final product, but otherwise, it's pretty darn\par
close to what shipped.  It's definitely what we used going into production.\par
This large file merges all 13 mission scripts with the planetside/base-side\par
story script (that was written & recorded first to allow production to begin on\par
the real-time cinematics).\par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 2) Intro Storyboards\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
Hollywood storyboard artist Marc Baird was brought in by Chris Roberts to 'board the\par
extravagant intro sequence, in 1998/1999.  Here are some of his storyboards.  After\par
watching the intro in its full glory on this DVD, you'll be able to understand the\par
storyboards better.\par
\par
The intro was created by Digital Anvil's visual effects team (after finishing the\par
Wing Commander movie) during 1999, and the 5.1 soundtrack was created by Soundelux\par
DMG in Hollywood, in February 2000.\par
\par
The anonymous narrator role, who in this DVD product is revealed as the character\par
of "Atticus Rockford", was performed by actor Xander Berkeley - who ALSO performs the\par
roles of Sam Lonnigan and Dexter Hovis later in the game (a pretty varied set of\par
performances there!).\par
\par
\f2 You can browse through the images and get some idea of the original thoughts behind\par
each shot.  OR use the Windows Media 9 file Curtis Neal created, to allow you to get\par
through them all in about two minutes.  Some of the storyboards may relate to\par
discarded ideas, so take them as they are.\f0\par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 3) Early music examples\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
I've included the earliest music we put into the game - from the Chris Roberts era.\par
The early music had an optimistic, "sea-going voyage" orchestral type of feel.  We\par
replaced it with a more modern, more sinister pseudo-electronic score in 2002\par
once the final character of the game was more evident.  Note - the "spotting" of\par
the music was also different back then - for example, a 2-minute piece for all\par
Liberty cityscapes, versus what we have now, which is one 20-second piece for each\par
planetscape (in the case of Liberty, there are six).  The early music was composed\par
by Visual Music's Dean Grindsfelder (Liberty & Pirates), Cato (Rheinland) and Osamu\par
Kitajima (Kusari - Osamu's only music in the shipping game is the suite of\par
planetscape tunes in Kusari).\par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 4 Extra music not on the CD\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
I've included the music for bars - mostly by Andrew Sega, but some by Tom Seufert of\par
Visual Music (which is the earliest music in the game that survived until the present\par
day).  Use \b Windows Media Player 6.4\b0  for perfect looping of these WAVs. (in your\par
\b Program Files\b0  folder)\par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 5 Movie tests/examples\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
We've included AVIs rendered out over the years, from ads & placards used in the\par
cityscapes, to artists' impressions of what the game will look like (\b DREAD.AVI\b0 ,\b\par
hud_ideas.avi\b0 ) to news broadcast visuals, that play underneath newsreader dialogue\par
(example - if it's a news clip about a new way to transport "solar gas" - the file\par
\b s37 solar gas.avi\b0  would be used).  There are also concepts for heads-up displays\par
in the game, ways to get your ship repaired, ways to get YOU repaired, etc..  As\par
you probably know, not all ideas, including the news clips, were used in the final\par
game.  \par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 6) Freelancer Story Character Vignettes\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
Jorg Neumann and Adam Foshko thought it would be cool to pad out the story's\par
fictional characters in a way that is not included in the story itself - offline,\par
so to speak.  So they created short speeches for each one, where they describe\par
themselves.  I can tell you, the actors enjoyed reading these vignettes probably\par
the most out of all their dialogue!  The vignettes are not 100% serious - there's\par
a bit of between-the-lines humour in each one.\par
\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-720\li720\cf1\b\f1\fs28 7) Intro Concept Art\cf0\b0\f0\fs20\par
\pard\par
We had concept artist Craig Mullens paint some magnificent pictures of events in\par
the intro story - colonists climbing into their sleeping pods, and the sleeper\par
ships before they launch.  These are pretty faithfully represented in the final\par
movie.\par
\par
